A CV-screening system falls under **Annex III, Category 4** of the EU AI Act — high-risk AI systems used in employment, workers management, and access to self-employment (specifically: recruitment, selection, promotion, and task allocation). As a high-risk system, it triggers the full obligations of Title III, Chapter 2 (Articles 9–15). The primary verifiable property to enforce is **non-discrimination / demographic parity across protected attributes** (sex, race, ethnic origin, religion, disability, age, sexual orientation per EU equality law). This must be measurable: compute selection rates per protected group and verify the 4/5ths (80%) rule or equal opportunity difference stays within accepted thresholds. Concretely, log model inputs/outputs (Article 12), maintain a bias audit trail, and test the selection-rate disparity on a held-out validation set stratified by protected attribute before each deployment. The technical documentation (Article 11) must record these disparity metrics and the corrective actions taken if thresholds are breached. A conformity assessment (Article 43) is required before market placement, and a human oversight mechanism (Article 14) must allow a recruiter to override or review every automated shortlisting decision.
